    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-12T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-12T06:00:00-05:00" n="477"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d477">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 942</seg>
                </opener>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">641.68/12–1251: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Yugoslavia (<persName corresp="#p_AGV1"
                            type="from">Allen</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d477fn1">Repeated to London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-12T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 12, 1951—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>779. Brit Amb and his staff have remarked to this <gloss target="#t_Emb1"
                        >Emb</gloss> re some cooling UK-Yugo relations last few weeks. They say
                    Yugos have been brusque as well as obstructive in their dealings here and have
                    also subjected staff to increased surveillance. Brit Amb inclined to attribute
                    this to Yugo reaction to UK Govt change, possibly <persName corresp="#p_CWS1"
                        >Churchill</persName>’s remark concerning recreating spirit war-time three
                    power conferences.<note n="2" xml:id="d477fn2">Regarding <persName
                            corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName>’s proposals for a three-power
                        meeting, see Document 449.</note>
                </p>
                <p>This <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> believes above as well as rankling
                    memories <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName>
                    <persName corresp="#p_S1">Stalin</persName> 50–50 deal on Yugo, may be partly
                    responsible but following are other likely factors: (1) Sir <persName
                        corresp="#p_DMF1">Francis Mudie</persName>’s critical attitude in tridel
                    econ discussions toward Yugo request for capital investment financing, (2)
                    decline Brit prestige Middle East, (3) replacement Peake by new Amb <persName
                        corresp="#p_MSV1">Mallet</persName> who is cooler and less colorful
                    personality although able representative. Conversely Yugo also annoyed by
                    Peake’s reported monarchical enthusiasm in Greece.</p>
                <p>It is possible Brit may be inclined exaggerate alleged Yugo slights due to
                    hypersensitivity resulting from secondary role Brit being forced to play in
                    international politics.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AGV1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Allen</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
